03886nam a2200529Ia 9781478059448DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20242024ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780594487 a10.1515/97814780594482doi  a(DE-B1597)690230  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBL2765.D44bM46 2024 7aSOC0080202bisacsh04a211/.6223/eng/202311171 aMenon, Nivedita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSecularism as Misdirection :bCritical Thought from the Global South /cNivedita Menon. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTheory in Forms : 1500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction Thinking Secularism from the Global South -- tThinking from the Global South -- tSecularism as Misdirection— A Map of the Book -- t1 State, Religion, and the Bodies of Women -- t2 Hindu Majoritarianism and the Construction of Religion -- t3 The Failed Project of Creating Hindus -- t4 The Self and Psychoanalysis from the Global South -- t5 Capitalism as Secular Science -- t6 Insurgent Constitutionalism and Radical Frames of Citizenship -- t7 Reshaping Worlds—Beyond the Capitalist Horizon -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Secularism as Misdirection, Nivedita Menon traces how the discourse of secularism fixes attention to and hypervisualizes women and religion while obscuring other related issues. Showing how secularism is often invoked to serve capital and antiminority politics, Menon exposes it as a strategy of governance that is compatible with both democracy and authoritarianism, capitalism and socialism. Secularism also delegitimizes the nonindividuated nonrational self, Menon argues; exploring this aspect, she tracks the journey of psychoanalysis in the global South. Menon further examines the interconnectedness of religion, caste, the state, and women, showing how the discourse of secularism can also be mobilized by Hindu supremacist politics in India. Menon puts Latin American decolonial theorists in conversation with Asian and African thinkers to examine twenty-first-century global reimaginings of selfhood, constitutionalism, citizenship, and anticapitalist existence. Through a feminist and global perspective, Menon suggests that transformative politics is better imagined by stepping out of the frame offered by secularism and focusing on substantive values such as democracy, social justice, and ecological justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPolitical culturezDeveloping countries. 0aReligion and statezDeveloping countries. 0aSecularismxPolitical aspectszDeveloping countries. 0aSecularismzDeveloping countries. 0aWomenzDeveloping countriesxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059448?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059448/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles